<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
  Managed-Debugging-Assistant (MDA) configuration for the editor process.

  THE BUG THIS BELONGS TO — "VS F5 hangs at the splash with only a 'Weiter/Continue' button":
  Under a managed debugger the CLR implicitly enables a set of MDAs. The 'disconnectedContext'
  assistant fires on the FINALIZER thread whenever an RCW is cleaned up after its COM apartment
  (a short-lived STA thread — VS's own injected XAML-diagnostics tap, TSF, or our STA file-picker
  threads) has already exited. That cleanup is harmless — the COM server is simply gone — but
  Visual Studio BREAKS for every occurrence during startup, and with the MDA dialog once dismissed
  ("don't show again") all that remains is a bare break-mode page with a Continue button: the
  editor looks frozen at the splash. Standalone runs are unaffected because MDAs only exist under
  a managed debugger — which is exactly why the exe always worked while F5 always "hung".

  THE PRIMARY FIX is in Visual Studio, not in this file: Debug > Windows > Exception Settings >
  Managed Debugging Assistants > UNCHECK 'DisconnectedContext' (and 'ContextSwitchDeadlock', which
  fires when our loader legitimately blocks the UI thread >60s). That setting is stored per
  solution/user (.suo) — re-apply it after a fresh clone or a VS settings reset.

  This file is the belt to that suspenders: the CLR reads "<exe name>.mda.config" next to the exe
  whenever the MDA infrastructure is activated EXPLICITLY (COMPLUS_MDA env var / MDA registry
  value). NOTE (verified 2026-07-05): under VS's plain F5 the implicitly-activated MDA set does
  NOT honor this file — the DisconnectedContext event still reached VS — so the Exception
  Settings change above is the one that actually stops the breaks.

  disconnectedContext   - RCW released after its (already-exited) apartment; benign cleanup noise.
  raceOnRCWCleanup      - same RCW-cleanup family, fires on the same benign teardown.
  contextSwitchDeadlock - fires after the UI thread blocks >60s; our loader legitimately blocks the
                          STA during heavy synchronous project/engine loads under the debugger.
-->
<mdaConfig xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/CLR/2004/10/mda">
  <assistants>
    <disconnectedContext enable="false" />
    <raceOnRCWCleanup enable="false" />
    <contextSwitchDeadlock enable="false" />
  </assistants>
</mdaConfig>
